<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: POST-TRAUMATIC STRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I read the column in which you said that even people who have never 
been in combat can have post-traumatic stress disorder. But does there have to 
have been a physical injury before a person can say that he has such a problem? 
And is there medicine to treat the condition, or is this something for which 
you need a psychiatrist? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Physical injury is not a prerequisite for a diagnosis of post-traumatic 
stress disorder. For example, a person who witnesses an automobile accident in 
which a friend or relative is killed may develop the disorder. 
</P>
<P>
Some antidepressants may be beneficial for some patients, and anti-anxiety 
therapy may be helpful for others. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
 Neil Solomon is author of "Sick &amp; Tired of Being Sick &amp; Tired," 
Wynwood Press. If you have a medical question, write to Dr. Solomon, P.O. Box 
36184, Baltimore, Md. 21285-6184. Solomon cannot give personal replies but will 
answer as many questions as possible in his column. 
</P>
</TEXT>
