on the air. The program is produced by media company Whittle Communications, 
which loans participating schools equipment and sells advertising to cover the 
cost. Despite bans by public educators in New York and California, 2,900 
schools have signed up. Said one student at a Tennessee high school where the 
program was shown, left: "I don't see why there is so much controversy over the 
commercials." He reported watching the same ads on regular TV at home. 
Associated Press 
</P>
